title: For Sale:  Custom Ruger 10/22 with Leupold scope/mount/rings
postcontent:
Custom Ruger 10/22. Has a Butler Creek .920" barrel and stock set installed. Leupold base and rings and Leupold Vari-X IIc 3-9 scope. Built on an older 10/22 with the aluminum triggerguard. Has an aftermarket extended mag release lever. Don't know if the internals are factory or aftermarket, but the trigger pull is somewhere between 1 and 2 pounds with just a touch of creep. Whoever customized it removed the bolt hold-open lever for some reason. Not a big deal to me, as I rarely use one in a 10/22 since they don't engage automatically. Very accurate gun - shot 1" groups at 50 yards with regular ammo off the bench. Does show some scattered freckling and some scattered wear/marks. Was this way when I got it. The worst is toward the muzzle. The pics make it look worse than it does in hand in regular light. Note that the freckling at the muzzle is around the rim of the crown and won't affect accuracy. I was going to have the barrel threaded for a suppressor, in which case that would all go away.

$480 FIRM, face to face in Hickory, NC. Not interested in separating the scope from the gun. Not interested in trades or offers. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Tri-Star Semi-Auto Tactical 12 Gauge Shotgun 5+1
postcontent: Up for sale is a fully functional, 100% reliable guaranteed 12 Gauge shotgun. I bought it brand new when it first hit the stores, and it's a damn good shotgun, I have no regrets for buying it over a Remington 870 (which I was going to buy instead). I was worried about reliability at first since it's walmart exclusive shotgun and I didn't see much on it on the internet, but it surprised me. About 20 target loads later and it was shooting reliably (a short break in period is expected of semi-auto shotguns). It shoots the target loads just normal, I have yet to even use any other loads in it. It features a 20" barrel and a muzzle break. It's possible to extend the capacity to 8+1 with a Remington 870 extension kit, but you need to shorten the threading by a hair. I'm selling this because I need to make rent, and I just really don't need a shotgun right now. I'm a gun nut, but being young I'm not as responsible as I'd like to be, so it's good I'm selling this. The price is firm at $320, but you basically save $35 in sales tax, plus I'm including a nice $20 hard plastic padded Plano carrying case, as well as 5 shots of 00 buckshot, and roughly 30 shells of a target load.

This is a high performance STANDARD PRESSURE 40 S&W loading, which means it is safe to fire in all 40 S&W chambered firearms that are in normal operating condition.

The lightweight 125gr. all copper Barnes bullet will mushroom readily, yet penetrate as deeply as a typical 165gr. JHP style bullet, while generating the low recoil and fast velocities of a light weight projectile. This aids in fast/accurate follow-up shots. Expect roughly 12 to 13 inches of penetration in living flesh and bone. 

This load utilizes a flash suppressed powder, which gives the shooter an important advantage as most shootings in the US occur in low light when the criminal element is most active. Firing to save your life in the dark is likely if you find yourself forced to fire. Blinding yourself with your first shot, leaves you very vulnerable.

Accuracy was excellent in every test pistol. Feeding and function was also 100% in every test pistol.

As always, we have used real world firearms to generate our published velocities. We feel the industry wide duplicitous practice of generating velocities from extra long laboratory barrels is dishonest to the customer as he/she will not be able to duplicate those velocities in the real world, where it matters.

1420 fps -- Caspian 1911, 5-inch barrel
1302 fps -- Taurus PT100, 4.7-inch barrel
1300 fps -- Glock Mod. 23, 4-inch barrel
1303 fps -- Kahr PM40, 3-inch barrel

You’ll note that the shortest barrel did not give the slowest velocity. This shows that there is often internal barrel dynamics that influence velocity, more than barrel length alone.
